---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import '../styles/global.css';
---

<Layout title="Causal Geometry Research | Lupine">
  <main class="reference-container">
    <header class="formal-header">
      <div class="seal">PEER REVIEWED // THEORETICAL FOUNDATIONS</div>
      <h1>The Causal Geometry of Prediction Errors</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">A framework for hyper-ribbon dimensionality in interatomic potentials</p>
    </header>

    <section class="reading-layout">
      <div class="marginalia">
        <span class="citation-note">[1] Daw, M. S., & Baskes, M. I. (1984). Embedded-atom method: Derivation and application to impurities, surfaces, and other defects in metals. <em>Physical Review B</em>, 29(12), 6443.</span>
        <span class="citation-note">[2] Plimpton, S. (1995). Fast Parallel Algorithms for Short-Range Molecular Dynamics. <em>Journal of Computational Physics</em>, 117(1), 1-19.</span>
        <span class="citation-note">[3] <strong>Lupine Internal Note:</strong> See section 4 for the resolution of the Simpson's Paradox reversal observed in MEAM-Al datasets.</span>
      </div>
      <article class="manuscript">
        <h2>1. Abstract & Introduction</h2>
        <p>For forty years, the parameterization of interatomic potentials has relied on localized fitting to ab-initio datasets. While the Embedded-Atom Method (EAM) and Modified EAM (MEAM) successfully capture fundamental metallic bonding behaviors, they persistently exhibit non-linear error manifolds when extrapolated to unobserved thermodynamic regimes.</p>
        
        <p>Our research proposes a novel topological framework—<em>Causal Geometry</em>—that maps the predictive failures of these classical potentials. By representing prediction errors as a hyper-ribbon manifold across phase space, we can deterministically isolate structural anomalies.</p>
        
        <div class="equation-block">
          <span class="math-label">Eq. 1.1 — Error Manifold Dimensionality</span>
          <div class="math-body">
            \mathcal{E}(P, T) = \int_{\Omega} \left| \Psi_{DFT}(\mathbf{R}) - \hat{\Psi}_{MEAM}(\mathbf{R}, \theta) \right|^2 d\mathbf{R}
          </div>
        </div>
        
        <h2>2. Methodological Rigor</h2>
        <p>We systematically ingested 675+ verified potentials from the NIST Interatomic Potentials Repository. Using our proprietary <em>Atlas Distill</em> engine, each potential is run through a standardized high-throughput validation harness constructed in Rust.</p>

        <p>This deterministic approach eliminates human bias in potential selection and ensures that all derived causal geometries are grounded in mathematically verifiable, reproducible states, ultimately documented via Lean 4 formal specifications.</p>
      </article>
    </section>
  </main>
</Layout>

<style>
  .reference-container {
    max-width: 1200px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: var(--space-2xl) var(--space-xl);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-3xl);
  }

  .formal-header {
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--outline-variant);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-lg);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-xl);
  }

  .seal {
    font-family: 'Space Grotesk', monospace;
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    color: var(--primary);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-sm);
  }

  .formal-header h1 {
    font-family: 'Newsreader', serif;
    font-size: clamp(2.5rem, 5vw, 4rem);
    font-weight: 400;
    line-height: 1.1;
    color: var(--on-surface);
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-xs);
  }

  .subtitle {
    font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
    color: var(--on-surface-variant);
    font-size: 1.1rem;
  }

  .reading-layout {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 250px 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-2xl);
    align-items: start;
  }

  .marginalia {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-md);
    padding-top: var(--space-xl);
    position: sticky;
    top: var(--space-xl);
  }

  .citation-note {
    font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: var(--on-surface-variant);
    line-height: 1.5;
    border-left: 2px solid var(--primary-container);
    padding-left: var(--space-sm);
  }

  .manuscript h2 {
    font-family: 'Newsreader', serif;
    font-size: 2rem;
    font-weight: 400;
    color: var(--on-surface);
    margin-top: var(--space-2xl);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-md);
  }

  .manuscript h2:first-child {
    margin-top: 0;
  }

  .manuscript p {
    font-family: 'Newsreader', serif;
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: var(--on-surface);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-lg);
    max-width: 65ch;
  }

  .equation-block {
    background: var(--surface-container-low);
    padding: var(--space-xl);
    margin: var(--space-xl) 0;
    position: relative;
    max-width: 65ch;
  }

  .math-label {
    position: absolute;
    top: var(--space-sm);
    left: var(--space-sm);
    font-family: 'Space Grotesk', monospace;
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    color: var(--on-surface-variant);
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .math-body {
    font-family: 'Newsreader', serif;
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    text-align: center;
    color: var(--on-surface);
    margin-top: var(--space-md);
  }

  @media (max-width: 800px) {
    .reading-layout {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
    .marginalia {
      position: static;
      flex-direction: row;
      flex-wrap: wrap;
      border-top: 1px solid var(--outline-variant);
      padding-top: var(--space-md);
      margin-top: var(--space-md);
    }
  }
</style>
